ot exactly — SPI and I²C are fundamentally different in how clocks and data work, so the “must send dummy bytes” rule in SPI doesn’t directly apply to I²C. Let me explain carefully.

1️⃣ Clock generation
SPI

Clock (SCLK) is generated by the master only when it shifts data out.

Receiving data is tied to transmitting data.

This is why the master must send a dummy byte to generate clocks when reading.

I²C

Clock (SCL) is also generated by the master.

But I²C is bidirectional by design, and the protocol allows the master to release the SDA line while still generating clocks.

So the master can generate clocks without sending “meaningful” data — no dummy bytes are strictly needed.

2️⃣ How data flows in I²C

SDA (data line) and SCL (clock line) are open-drain, pulled up by resistors.

The master can toggle the clock and let the slave drive the data line.

Example: reading a byte from a slave:

Master releases SDA
Master generates 8 clock pulses on SCL
Slave outputs 8 bits on SDA
Master reads SDA

No need to send any “dummy” data — just generate clocks.

This is fundamentally half-duplex, unlike SPI full-duplex.

3️⃣ Comparison of SPI vs I²C reads
Feature	SPI	I²C
Duplex	Full-duplex	Half-duplex
Data transfer tied to clock	Yes → must transmit to receive	No → master can generate clock while reading
Dummy byte required?	Yes	No
Clock type	Driven by master’s transmit shift register	Master can generate clock independently
4️⃣ Why SPI is still faster

Even though SPI needs dummy bytes:

SPI clocks are much faster (MHz range)

No start/stop/ACK overhead per byte

Full duplex → can transmit and receive simultaneously

I²C:

Lower speed (100 kHz – 3.4 MHz)

Half duplex

Many protocol overhead bits (address, ACK/NACK, start/stop)

So effective throughput is lower

✅ Key takeaway

SPI: read = transmit dummy + receive, because the hardware ties clocks to shifting the TX register.

I²C: read can happen just by generating clocks, because master and slave can manage the data line independently.
